node.text: “At the end of my days, in my declining hours, I want to look in the mirror and see somebody who cared and tried to do all that he could to try to save nature as I know it and as I love it." node.text: Sharing our gratitude for nature with one another is a small but meaningful way to honor and connect with our world and with each other. If we don’t savor nature while working to protect it, we risk losing sight of what we’re trying to save. I’m teaming up with @world_wildlife to invite you to share your love of nature with a photo or video that embodies that love. This week’s theme is wildlife, so here at the Photo Ark we are celebrating the diversity of aquatic species found around the globe. Share your appreciation for the natural world by using the hashtag #WhyILoveNature and tell us the story behind your post and @world_wildlife may re-post your share to their account! #ShowYourLoveForNature #photoark

Today we’re crossing the 10,000 species mark with the güiña, a small wild cat photographed @fauna_andina in Chile! It’s been 15 years in the making, and we’ll keep going until we get every species in human care around the world - once the pandemic subsides, of course. Please join us in celebrating this milestone, and think about the ways that you can save species; reduce, reuse, recycle... but also insulate your home well, plant a pollinator garden, and never use chemicals of any kind on your lawn. You know the drill.
From all of us at Team Photo Ark, thank you. Now, let’s save them all! #PhotoArk #savetogether

node.text: Fourteen years ago, this project was created to try to get the world to care about the extinction crisis and inspire people around the globe to take action to save wildlife. A lot has changed since the project began - some species have seen their numbers rise for the first time in decades, many have been discovered and described by scientists for the first time, while others, sadly, have been lost forever. The world around us is constantly changing - a fact that is felt by each of us now more than ever as the current pandemic continues to alter our behaviors and the ways in which we interact with the world around us. We know things are tough right now, and it can be hard to feel like you’re making a difference in the world when you’re stuck in isolation, so today, we’re asking you to share both your challenges and successes when it comes to taking action to save wildlife in the comments section below. Throughout the year, we will continue to share tips and tricks on how you can save species from the comfort of your own home, and do our best to answer all of your saving-wildlife questions. Remember, no matter where you are, we are all in this together. #PhotoArk #savetogether #EarthDay

node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ Originally from the south-central region of the United States, red swamp crayfish have now been transplanted all over the world, from Hawaii to Japan and even the Nile River where they are considered an invasive species. This species is well-known for its burrowing behavior which helps them find food, moisture, and provides a safe space for molting (shedding their exoskeleton and growing a new one). While crayfish are a valuable human food source, they also play an important role in controlling populations of aquatic snails that are responsible for spreading pathogens to humans. Video taken @woodlandparkzoo. #swamp #crayfish #red #PhotoArk #15YearsofPhotoArk

node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ Native to West Africa, pygmy goats were first brought to the United States in the 1950s. This domesticated species may be small in stature but their personalities are mega-sized, with the goats being known for their friendliness and intelligence. While they are often seen in captive settings, pygmy goats can also be spotted in the wild where they spend much of their time browsing for leaves. node.text:
15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ Ever hear of a Palawan stink badger? I hadn’t either until the staff at the @avilonzooph told me they had one. Sounded interesting, and since I was going there with a team from @60minutes , anything out of the ordinary was welcome fare.

On the first morning of shooting, the zoo staff brought over the little guy. He was cute as can be and smaller than I expected, with a pointy nose and a striped rear end, which he quickly pointed at me and released a thick, white fluid that smelled exactly like...skunk.

It made for good television of course, but I immediately thought, how did an animal that evolved on a Pacific island come up with an odor just like an American skunk? Convergent evolution, of course. This is when unrelated species, often separated by great distances, develop similar solutions for problems. In the case of the two skunk species, they’ve both come up with the nastiest-smelling chemicals they can to ward off predators.

It sure worked well in our case. We finished the shoot in record time and sent him on his way. The smell was so bad we had to scrub and scrub our shooting crate, with little effect.

15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ Many years ago, when I was first starting to work on the Photo Ark, I decided that using a paper background for great apes would be a good idea.

It wasn’t.

I drove from my home in Lincoln to the @sunsetzoomhk. Their troop of chimpanzees was in their huge outdoor enclosure as my son and I readied an off exhibit space for the photo shoot. We’d brought a roll of heavy, white paper, then cut it to fit perfectly, including the floor. Plenty of heavy duct tape held everything in place, and after about an hour, we were all set with the entire room a picture-perfect white. What could possibly go wrong?

Plenty, it turned out.

The chimps took one look at the set up from a nearby stall, but didn’t go in the room. Instead, one of the larger chimps stuck one arm in and pulled the entire set down; in one swift grab, all the paper was yanked out through a side door. The entire demolition didn’t even take ten seconds.

I could hear the chimps vocalizing as they began to tear up the paper into little tiny bits. They had a lot of fun.

Me, not so much. We packed up the lights and began the long drive back home, empty handed.

Today we use paint on the walls and floor to do all our great ape portraits. At least that way we know we’ll get our pictures...at least until the chimps learn how to peel paint.

node.text: 15 Years of Photo Ark Celebration/ Himalayan monal pheasants are one of the most admired pheasant species in the world, largely due to the male’s beautiful array of brightly-colored feathers. As it turns out, we aren’t the only ones mesmerized by his striking looks - his bold colors and feathered crest are actually intended to help him find a mate. This species has a wide distribution, ranging from eastern Afghanistan to southwestern China. With a stable population, your chances of seeing one of these birds in the wild are good, though illegal hunting may soon become a threat to the highly sought after pheasant. Photo taken at Pheasant Heaven. #pheasant #Himalayan #monalpheasant #bird #male #colorful #stunning #beautiful #PhotoArk #15YearsofPhotoArk
